            ">Pope Francis's health update</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/catholic-chief-hospitalized-lung-infection-week.png" alt="The Catholic chief has been hospitalized for a week with a lung infection" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">The Catholic chief has been hospitalized for a week with a lung infection. Credits: ALBERTO PIZZOLI/AFP via Getty Images</p>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Pope Francis is in Rome's Gemelli Hospital <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/ps-24-02-2025-h1-1-battling-pneumonia-and-complex-lung-infection?source=website" target="_blank">battling pneumonia and complex lung infection</a>. His blood results show early signs of kidney failure, but the doctors said it was under control. In their latest update, the Vatican said he received high flows of supplementary oxygen and had no respiratory crisis. “The complexity of the clinical picture and the necessary wait for drug therapies to provide some feedback dictate that the prognosis remains guarded,” the Pope’s doctor said.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px)">On Saturday, the Vatican warned about the condition of the Pope after he suffered a prolonged asthma-style attack and needed blood transfusions for a low platelet count. He is still receiving oxygen through a cannula. In his Sunday Angelus prayer, Francis thanked the health staff and asked for prayers. He was admitted on February 14 for bronchitis and has had worsening symptoms.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
